Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China

We are living in a world in transition… A new economic and political order is still taking shape.

— Prime Minister Scott Morrison, 2019 Lowy Institute Lecture


While historic wildfires had certainly dampened economic activity, Australia had nonetheless completed its 28th year of positive GDP growth in 2019. The country seemed immune to recession –even in the global financial crisis of 2009. But now that mining investments had slowed and the housing boom stabilized, it was difficult to project future growth approaching 2% annually. Still, recent performance and conservative government had gone a long way towards eliminating the fiscal deficit. Unemployment was low, inflation even lower, and the current account balance had finally turned positive. Yet, some economists worried about the size of foreign debt, which continued to grow.

On the economic front, competitiveness was the overriding issue. While resource extraction was carrying the weight of growth and trade, productivity remained low and costs, high. While Australia continued to exhibit strengths in services – tourism, education and banking - it seemed unable to produce goods that were internationally competitive.

Taken together, these conditions put China at the center of Australia’s worries. China now dominated the Pacific region in terms of trade, competitiveness and sheer size. But Australia, a liberal democracy, still depended on security from its relationship with Western powers with whom it was more culturally aligned– particularly the United States. As the relationship between China and the US had deteriorated in recent years, Australia’s economic footing, geopolitical strategy and cultural legacy were slowly unhinging.

Could Scott Morrison and his Liberal Party effectively help reposition Australia in this newly emerging world order?

720-028 Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China


The Land Down Under1

Australia is the smallest and flattest of continents, located between the Indian and South Pacific Oceans. European records dated the discovery of Australia by Dutch traders and Spanish explorers in the 17th century, but the aboriginal civilization is one of the oldest in the world, dating back at least 65,000 years.2 It was not until 1770 that Captain James Cook sailed his ship, HM Bark Endeavour, along the eastern coast of Australia and claimed it as British territory under the name ”New South Wales.” In 1788, Britain established a penal colony in what became known as Sydney (New South Wales) and eventually claimed five additional colonies: Queensland, South Australia, Northern Territory, Victoria and Western Australia. These colonial economies flourished through the export of wool, food and raw materials, while Britain was the major source of capital investments and migrants. A gold rush hit in the 1850s, during which time Victoria was producing more than one-third of the world’s gold, luring immigrants from Europe and China.3

In 1901, the Commonwealth of Australia was officially established as a federation of the six colonies and as part of Great Britain. Even then, the new federation was the richest country in the world, thanks to its minerals and sheep.4 Key objectives of the new federation revolved around expanding employment in manufacturing, maintaining a high level of real wages and reducing the impact of volatility from international commodity and capital markets.5 Following the prevailing views among political circles that protection raised real wages and allowed large employment,6 Australia gradually shifted towards a more inward-oriented government policy, encouraging domestic manufacturing through tariff protection.

The end of WWII marked the beginning of a long period of economic prosperity around the world; Australia was no exception. A mining boom in the 1960s unleashed the discovery of new minerals ranging from alumina to zinc in the Northwest, which was generally isolated from the densely populated cities of the southeast coast. Japan’s rapidly growing steel industry created demand for Australia’s coking coal and iron ore. Eager to tap into its natural endowment of resources, the government encouraged greater investments in mining through generous tax incentives. Since the mining industry required large-scale, capital-intensive investments, foreign capital was welcomed. As a result, coal production alone doubled between 1969 and 1979, and mineral products provided a quarter of Australia’s export receipts by 1970–1971.7 Australia soon achieved one of the world’s highest living standards.

Oil Shocks and the Rise of Inflation

The first oil shock in 1974 disrupted the balance of the Australian economy. A severe contraction in world demand led to reduced exports, a deepening of the current account deficit, and the exposure of weaknesses in the Australian economy. By 1975, Australia’s average tariff on imports had risen to above 12%, while average tariffs for other developed countries had declined towards 2% during the same period.8 Protectionism, however, did not help productivity growth.

Australia also faced rapid wage growth and rising inflation. The average non-farm wage rate almost doubled in the four years prior to 1975.9 An “award” system, which defined work conditions ranging from hours to salaries, reduced flexibility in real wages. A pay raise in one sector would spill over to other industries and occupations under the motif of “comparative wage justice.” This not only drove up overall wages but also created a mismatch of salaries in less productive sectors of the economy.10 Inflation, as a consequence, soared to almost 18% in 1975. The collapse of fixed exchange rates in 1971 also gave way to a more lax monetary policy. Malcolm Fraser, the new prime minister in 1975, declared “fight inflation first” as his policy amid the crisis of stagflation. Yet, six years after his declaration,

inflation remained above 11%.11 Meanwhile, economic growth had slowed while wages continued to rise.

Fighting Inflation and Reforms

By the early 1980s, dissatisfaction with the Fraser administration ushered in a new Labor regime led by Bob Hawke (1983-1991), a former trade union president who was elected to become prime minister after serving only two years in Parliament. As a Rhodes Scholar studying at Oxford University, Hawke marked a page in The Guinness Book of Records for drinking 2.5 pints of beer in just 11 seconds. “It endeared me to a large section of the Australian voting population,” admitted Hawke.12

As its chief anti-inflation tool, the Hawke administration relied on the 1983 Wages and Prices Accord; this agreement restrained wage increases by committing trade union members to anti-inflationary bargaining measures by indexing wages to the consumer price index. In December of that year, the government floated the Australian dollar. The float was accompanied by the Reserve Bank of Australia’s (RBA) new policy of avoiding intervention and pursuing a “hands off” approach. The government also adopted measures to liberalize the financial sector, lifting exchange controls, permitting offshore portfolio investments and removing entry restrictions on foreign banks.

Despite these structural changes, Australia’s balance-of-payment problem deepened. As the current account deficit surged to 6% of GDP, Treasurer Paul Keating (who would replace Hawke as prime minister in 1991) warned that Australia was in danger of becoming a “banana republic,” and he subsequently developed a “CAD [current account deficit] mania.”13 Real short-term interest rates were hiked to levels higher than any OECD country,14 in the belief that monetary policy was a key tool that could help correct the imbalances. Tighter money, it was thought, would slow imports and reduce the deficit, thereby easing downward pressure on the local currency and upward pressure on inflation. Yet as one critic noted, this measure was “akin to bandaging a burst blood vessel.”15

There was also a growing concern that the pace of foreign borrowing was unsustainable and that policymakers could and should do something to address the imbalance. Corporations increasingly depended on foreign debt to finance investments. Households went on a credit binge. As a result, Australia’s net external liabilities/GDP doubled from 23% in the 1980-81 fiscal year to 46% in the 1989-90 fiscal year; net foreign debt surged from 6% to over 35% during the same time period.16

Financial Downturn and Recession

In a desperate attempt to control inflation, the RBA raised its discount rate to 18% by November 1989. “It seems clear,” observed Bernie Fraser, the acting governor of the RBA in 1990, “that even moderate rates of inflation of the kind we have been experiencing recently do impose sufficient costs on the community to warrant determined efforts to do better.”17

Not surprisingly, the economy plunged into recession. Commercial property prices tumbled, excessive credit borrowing was spotlighted, bad loans soared and unemployment rose above 10%. The RBA now found itself lacking credibility to fight inflation after muddling through the last decade without a clear and coherent monetary policy. As one journalist noted, “The problem with Australia is that everyone has come to believe that the central bank will never be serious about extinguishing inflation … And there is no constituency in Australia—be it voters, the farmers, the miners, the retailers, the builders, the manufacturers or the unions—which want to get rid of inflation that badly.”18 Comments such as Keating’s defiant words that “it was a recession we had to have,” had little resonance.


3

Policymakers tried to tackle the situation under a renewed commitment to “snap the inflation stick and bring Australia back into the community of its OECD partners.”19 In 1993, the RBA made a crucial decision to conduct monetary policy under the principle of targeting an average underlying inflation rate of 2-3% over the medium term.a Additional reforms were implemented: double-digit tariffs were nearly eliminated to average around 5% by 1996, public enterprises were privatized in key industries, and regulatory reforms opened up sectors to competition. Hawke and Keating (1991-1996) also devoted their efforts to strengthening Australia’s relationship with the Asia-Pacific region. As one observer noted, these two leaders had “fundamentally converted the nation’s traditional protectionist mentality to the idea that living standards of Australians depend on their ability to trade their way in the global marketplace.”20

Although the Labor Party’s reforms transformed Australia, the public was not forgiving of the painful experience of high unemployment and high inflation. In 1996 John Howard, Leader of the Opposition, took over the helm as prime minister after a sweeping victory by the Liberal-National Party coalition.

A Return to Growth

From 1995 to 2006, the Australian economy grew at 4.4% annually.21 The soundness and resilience of the Australian economy were tested by the devastating Asian financial crisis (1997-1998) and global economic slowdown following the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks in the US. Each time, Australia’s growth recovered quickly, making the nation’s economy, in Howard’s words, “the envy of the industrialized world.”22 With full independence granted in 1996, the RBA continued with its mantra to control inflation. State enterprises in transportation and telecommunications were privatized. Another wave of labor relations reform came in 1996 with the Workplace Relations Act, which permitted individual contracts and further reduced what workers could receive through awards. Union membership continued to decline, representing just above a fifth of the workforce by 2003. Additionally, the federal government’s fiscal deficit was eliminated in 1997.

Howard was also a strong advocate of bilateral trade agreements, which led to free-trade agreements with the United States, Singapore and Thailand. A major stimulus for growth came from the global commodity boom that emerged in the early 2000s, which drove Australia’s terms of trade— the ratio of export to import prices—to levels not seen over the previous three decades (Exhibit 13). Record profits by natural resources companies led corporate tax receipts to more than double in the last six years to A$73 billion.


The Labor Party’s Comeback

Despite Australia’s robust economic health, the conservative leadership had begun losing popularity. The government’s support of the Iraq War, together with its excessively pro-business views resulted in a Labor victory for Kevin Rudd (2007-2010) in November 2007. Rudd, a fresh face in Australian politics, had risen to the helm of Labor’s opposition as a one-time dairy farmer with diplomatic experience in China. He quickly implemented campaign promises – including issuing an official apology to the aboriginal people and ratifying the Kyoto Protocol.

The Great Recession

Triggered by the collapse of America’s subprime industry in 2007 and resulting liquidity shortfall in the US banking system during the next year, the United States slumped into a sharp recession. Two investment banks and several mortgage lenders went bankrupt. By 2009, the crisis had spread to nonfinancial sectors and economies around the world. Global GDP fell by 5%, and unemployment rates rose to 9% in industrial nations. Exports plunged by 17%.23

Australian banks, thanks to limited exposure to toxic subprime mortgages, remained relatively healthy. Still, Australian consumers tightened their belts as the value of their housing and equity stocks started to decline. Business confidence tumbled to a record low, and capacity utilization dropped sharply. Risk aversion spread to currency markets whereby the Australian dollar seemed less attractive. Tighter world credit markets following the US subprime meltdown showed signs of adding stress to Australia’s current account deficit as banks sought more long-term loans from offshore markets, rising from $2.9 billion in the third quarter of 2007 to $18.5 billion in the fourth quarter.24

Commodity prices took a 10% nosedive—their worst performance in 28 years.25 Demand from China softened as raw material prices tumbled, with the World Bank forecasting double-digit declines in 2009.26 Chinese steelmakers cut orders and the Australian dollar experienced a sudden depreciation to five-year lows (see Exhibit 2). The impact of falling commodity prices and slower growth in China were particularly troublesome, given that China had purchased more than 21% of Australia’s commodity exports.27 Investors, moreover, had begun to worry about a political battle brewing in Australia over the country's ties to China.

Stimulus Spending and Loose Monetary Policy

As a global recession appeared imminent, the Rudd administration moved swiftly to take dramatic measures amid the deteriorating situation. In October 2008, the government announced that it would completely guarantee deposits and wholesale borrowing for insured financial institutions. The move, intended to calm jittery nerves in the markets, immediately sparked criticism and a massive exodus from non-guaranteed funds and trusts into deposits at guaranteed institutions such as banks and credit unions.

The Rudd government aggressively pushed forward with fiscal stimulus packages as well. The first package, worth A$8.7 billion, consisted of cash payments to low-income households in December 2008, followed by an additional A$12.2 billion the following year.28 As households sought to reduce their exposure to debt, the Rudd administration approved another stimulus package of A$42 billion in 2009. With tax receipts shrinking, the fiscal balance turned negative, falling to -4.2% of GDP.29 Critics of the package claimed that the fiscal spending was simply too big; former Opposition Leader Malcolm Turnbull claimed that the stimulus was “… about twice as big as we should be spending at the moment. We shouldn’t be firing all of our shots at once; we’ve got to keep some shots in the locker.”30 Yet Rudd insisted, “Nobody likes being in deficit, and I don’t like being in deficit at all. This is not a question of choice. This is what we are required to do.”31 In April 2009, Rudd commanded a confidence rating of 65%, compared to Turnbull’s 21%.32

The RBA, meanwhile, had loosened monetary policy at a dizzying speed. It temporarily set aside concerns about inflation, which exceeded the target 2-3% range, and lowered interest rates to 3% by April 2009. Monetary easing seemed to have some positive effects as new home loans rose for the fourth consecutive month, driven by first-time home buyers who sought to take advantage of lower mortgage rates and government incentives. One economist at the central bank noted that lower borrowing rates

had reduced households’ debt-servicing burden by about 5% of their disposable income, providing a “significant amount of cash flow relief.”33

Surviving the Global Financial Crisis

Throughout Rudd’s tenure as prime minister, economic growth was negative for only one quarter, with GDP growing again in the first quarter of 2009 (Exhibit 2). He claimed that his first stimulus package, referred to as the “cash splash,” was successful in boosting retail trade and avoiding further negative growth. By December 2008, retail spending was back up by 3.8%, aiding the economy back into positive growth by the first quarter of 2009. However, the A$62.9 billion in stimulus spending left critics worried about the growing deficit, exacerbated by the decline in tax revenues after the slowdown in mining.34

As Australia appeared to have escaped the worst of the global economic downturn, the RBA increased interest rates to 4.5% while the government adjusted fiscal policies to reflect an economy in recovery. And the housing bubble returned. Rising inflation, in addition to a shortage of 200,000 homes, had driven Australian housing prices skyward. In 2010, the average cost of an Australian home was 82% higher than homes in the U.S.35 RBA Governor Glenn Stevens stated that the decision to raise the interest rate to 4.5% was an attempt to combat the rampant inflation of the housing market and prevent the bubble from bursting.

The Labor Party’s New Leader

Notwithstanding this quick recovery, Rudd was unpopular even in his own party. His back-down on a trading scheme for carbon emissions, combined with an apparent arrogance that led party leaders to worry about his ability to win in a general election, resulted in a unanimous vote in June 2010 to replace him with Julia Gillard (2010-2013), his deputy prime minister, and the first female prime minister of Australia. This internal shift in leadership signified growing problems for the Labor Party. The August general election resulted in a hung parliament, with Labor winning only 72 seats in the House of Representatives in comparison to the 73 seats held by the Liberal-Nationals. In order to form a minority government, the Labor Party was forced to court three Independent MPs and one member of the Green Party, a move that ensured a narrow victory for the Labor Party, but obligated Gillard to grant concessions to these groups throughout her tenure as prime minister.

The Structure of Australia’s Economy

The economy Gillard inherited was doing comparatively well in relation to the global community. In 2008, Australia ranked 7th of 55 countries in national competitiveness and 3rd on the Human Development Index of the United Nations. With rising demand (especially in China) for resources, large Australian mining companies (such as BHP Billiton and Rio Tinto) had secured record increases in contract prices for exports of iron ore and coal. Unemployment hit a low of 4.2%, inflation was low and the exchange rate was strengthening. GDP per capita, at $49,200, exceeded the US by almost $1,000. Yet by 2020, Australia’s ranking in competitiveness had slipped to sixteenth, just behind France,36 and on the Human Development Index, to sixth.37

The structure of Australia’s economy was still fairly balanced before the crisis. Agricultural products contributed 10% of exports, crude materials 25%, fuel 22%, and manufactured goods, 19% (Exhibit 10). The service sector was particularly strong; business services, financial services, education and tourism all contributed significantly (28%) to the country’s exports. House construction and home prices were again booming.


6

Despite these strengths, productivity growth and competitiveness were lagging. Growth of manufacturing productivity in Australia was negative – worse than all other developed countries. This was particularly severe in the mining and utility sectors (Exhibit 5a). This decline was primarily the result of a strong global demand for raw resources, which rapidly increased commodity prices, thus creating a greater incentive to access difficult-to-extract deposits.38 While the higher prices for raw mineral exports had offset the mining industry’s productivity slowdown, weak productivity in non-mining industries meant lower real incomes for producers and higher costs for consumers.39

From 2009–2010, the cost of coal rose 37.8%, and the cost of aluminum jumped by 30.5%.40 Yet, according to some critics, this quick rebound was something of a double-edged sword. Skeptics argued that Australia had developed an economy that was too dependent on commodity exports and that the success of the mining industry was unsustainable. They also contended that the declining productivity of the mining industry was responsible for Australia’s lagging productivity growth throughout the 2000s.41 Yet because of the mining boom, wages were rising faster than most of its competitors (Exhibit

6), leaving the country with higher and higher unit labor costs. (Exhibit 7).

Additionally, it appeared that Australia had developed what was usually referred to as a “two-speed economy,” in which growth of the raw mineral sector significantly outgrew the nation’s other industries. Over the 2011-2012 fiscal year, the RBA estimated that the mining industry grew 12%, while only 2% growth was measured within the non-mining sectors.

One issue was the lack of investment in research and development by Australian businesses. Australia’s chief scientist, Alan Pettigrew, warned that such low investment had hindered the competitiveness of the country’s manufacturing sector.42 Moreover, in the event that either prices or demand for global commodity goods dropped, low investment placed Australia at a disadvantage for transitioning toward greater innovation-led productivity (Exhibits 3a and 3b).

While the mining sector now dominated Australia’s economy, a majority of Australians lived far away from the west coast mines, requiring the mining industry to offer substantial incentives to relocate. To attract workers, the mining industry offered extremely generous salaries and working schedules, which the manufacturing and retail sectors were unable to match. In 2011, the manufacturing and retail sectors lost 50,000 jobs, while 60,000 jobs were created within the mining industry.43 Regional disparities were growing even wider with commodity-rich Western Australia and Queensland prospering faster than other states. There had even been calls for more open immigration policies to meet the skilled labor shortage in these two states.

By 2018, the growth of labor productivity had slowed to a 0.2%; total factor productivity, to 0.4% (Exhibit 5b). The Productivity Commission attributed this weakness to the “marked slowdown in investment in capital – so much so that the ratio of capital to labour has fallen – [resulting in] ‘capital shallowing.’”44 Capital input had merely increased by 1.9% in 2017-18, well below the historical averaged of 4%. “This is troubling because investment typically embodies new technologies, which complement people’s skill development and innovation.”45

Domestic Concerns and Political Issues

Gillard also faced a number of domestic issues, including a carbon tax, mineral taxes, immigration and asylum seekers, healthcare reform, and implementation of the National Broadband Network.

Before the 2010 election, Gillard had publicly promised that a carbon tax (proposed and then abandoned by her predecessor) would not be implemented. However, as a concession to the Green Party, Labor enacted a carbon tax in November 2011. The tax charged A$23 per ton of carbon emission



7

720-028 Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China



and applied to the 300 worst-polluting companies. Gillard contended that the tax was the only feasible means to meet Australia’s climate change obligations, as the nation produced 18.75 tons of carbon dioxide per individual, among the highest in the world. Although implemented on July 1, 2012, this tax was supported by only one-third of Australians; utilities and the mining industry were strongly opposed. Critics argued that the tax raised the cost of living, while contributing to unemployment as businesses struggled to meet the new expense. Opposition Leader Tony Abbott declared that he would repeal the tax if the Liberal Party won in 2013.

In a separate attempt to raise government revenue (and reduce the deficit), a Mineral Resources Rent Tax (MRRT) placed a 30% tax on annual profits (above A$75 million) earned by firms mining coal and iron ore. Taking effect on July 1, 2012, the tax was projected to generate A$12 billion by the 2013-2014 fiscal year. Revenue from the tax was earmarked for several purposes, including reducing the corporate tax rate from 30% to 29% and funding infrastructure. Yet the mining industry claimed that the tax would force billions of dollars of investments elsewhere. Australia’s third-largest iron-ore exporter, Fortescue Metals Group Ltd., claimed that the MRRT was “unfair, narrowly based, complex, inefficient, and will reduce investment and future jobs in the Australian mining industry.”46

With regard to the National Broadband Network (NBN), the Commonwealth government aimed to extend broadband service to 3.5 million homes and businesses, effectively connecting all Australian premises to high-speed Internet access. As Australia’s largest infrastructure project to date, the NBN was estimated to cost a total of A$36 billion, of which A$27.5 billion fell entirely on the taxpayer.47 In March 2012, Australia’s government decided to ban the Chinese telecommunications company, Huawei, from supplying the necessary equipment for the NBN out of concern for cyber espionage.

While Gillard was able to pass these three “flagship policies” of the Labor Party— the carbon tax, MRRT, and the NBN—she was still left to contend with health-care reform and the growing number of asylum seekers. The National Health Reform Agreement (NHRA), passed in August 2011, aimed to reduce the financial burden placed on state governments and to improve hospital efficiency. For local and state governments, the burden of the cost of healthcare had increasingly become a concern; government calculations estimated that by 2045, the entirety of local and state government revenue would not be enough to cover the rising costs of healthcare. Under the NHRA, the Commonwealth government pledged to increase its contribution to growth funding for public hospitals to 50%, an increase of A$16.4 billion between 2014 and 2020.

The growing number of individuals seeking asylum in Australia also stood at the top of the political issues facing Gillard. For the first half of 2012, policymakers sat in deadlock over the future of the asylum seekers. Later that year, the government shifted policy and re-opened the refugee detention centers on the islands of Nauru and Manus (off Papua New Guinea), at a cost of billions of dollars.48 The refugees there would pose significant problems for Liberals, when they returned to power.

Foreign Flows and Balance of Payments Concerns

Between 1950 and 2019, Australia‘s current account had been in the red for all but four years (Exhibit 8). By 2010, booming exports driven by a commodities surplus had finally driven the trade surplus positive. Yet critics noted that the increase in product prices had not been accompanied by the same pace of growth in export volume; in the five years leading up to 2006, export volume growth had averaged 1.25%, far below the average of 7.5% for the previous 15 years.49

Mining companies found themselves spending their profits on importing new equipment and machinery to increase their mining capacity. Between 2000 and 2011, Australia’s imports of machinery and transportation equipment had surged 57% to A$80.84 billion, representing the single biggest


8

Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China 720-028


category of imports (see Exhibit 10). Natural resource companies also blamed the increasing shortage of skilled workers as a major supply-side constraint that held back growth in export volume. Bottlenecks caused by poor infrastructure—such as insufficient rail links and port capacity—had to be addressed as well. It had been reported that at one point, 79 ships were waiting in line at Newcastle, Australia’s biggest coal port, costing the companies tens of millions of dollars in delay charges.50

A more optimistic view of this current account deficit emerged in Australia from John Pitchford, a professor at the Australian National University.51 He argued that the deficit reflected households’ choice to consume now rather than save, companies’ desire to invest, and foreign investors’ willingness to lend under the expectation that they would be repaid. Believing that the situation was largely driven by these private actors rather than the government, Pitchford concluded that the current account deficit was the result of decisions made by “consenting adults.” Although some questioned whether people had the knowledge to make the best decisions, the consenting-adults view gained support among Australian policymakers, further cementing the central bank’s belief that monetary policy should focus only on inflation. In 2004, the acting deputy governor of the RBA reiterated, “The current account is not, and should not, be an objective of monetary policy.”52

Contrary to criticisms that the superannuation guarantee led to low savings, evidence suggested that it actually helped to increase overall savings in Australia.53 The “superannuation guarantee” required employers to put aside 9.5% of employees’ salaries into a retirement (or superannuation) fund. Some observers argued that Australia’s savings rate was no longer significantly lower than other OECD countries. Household savings had continued to increase following the financial crisis of 2008-2009. Yet by 2019 Australian households were only saving an estimated at 3.5% of their disposable income (excluding superannuation); wealth was maintained through appreciating homeownership.54

Because of the nation’s advanced financial system, Australia could issue debt denominated in its own currency.55 This reduced Australia’s vulnerability to foreign exchange market volatility. A former RBA governor noted, “If you have the ability to borrow abroad in your own currency, then you’d be relaxed about letting your exchange rate move a lot,” and thereby encourage foreigners to hold their assets.56 Australia was also a major player in the currency derivative markets where domestic financial institutions actively hedged and passed along their exchange rate risk to foreign investors willing to enter Australian-dollar-denominated derivative contracts.

To meet the shortfall between domestic savings and investment, foreign capital came to represent a significant source of funding for Australia; gross external debt reached 114% of GDP in 2019; net debt stood at about 49% of GDP.57 Investors were attracted by Australia’s political stability, coupled with favorable investment regulations and business conditions. Foreign investment was also a sensitive issue. One of the earliest rejections of foreign investment occurred in 2001 when the government blocked Dutch oil giant Shell’s A$10 billion bid for Woodside, Australia’s largest energy company, citing conflict with national interest. China’s growing interest in Australian resource companies also started to draw attention to the desirability of foreign investment.


Resurgence of Liberal Rule

In June of 2013, Kevin Rudd’s backers forced a leadership vote. In a reversal of the vote three years earlier, Rudd ousted Gillard to become prime minister…again. However, his victory was short-lived. Three months later, in a general election, Tony Abbott (2013-2015) prevailed, ending the Labor Party’s six-year reign. On election night, Abbott pledged to undo the flagship programs instituted under Gillard.


9

720-028 Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China



First, as part of Operation Sovereign Borders, Abbott set about “turning back the boats.” His administration’s policy used the military to tow boats back to their ports of origin, urged Indonesia to augment police oversight, and even spied on Indonesian communications. A violent riot occurred at the Manus detention center in 2014 over the failure to process cases, and in 2015, the Australian Human Rights Commission found 233 instances of child abuse at the Nauru center. Abbott, apparently, felt little guilt: “The most compassionate thing you can do is stop the boats. We have stopped the boats.”58

As he had promised during his campaign, Abbott introduced the repeal bill for the carbon tax during the first meeting of the new Parliament, claiming that the tax was an A$9 billion handbrake on the economy.59 Manufacturers and Australia’s main chamber of commerce, among others, opposed the carbon tax: BHP Billiton declared it harmful to Australia’s competitiveness, and Virgin Australia Holdings Ltd. said that the tax had cost them millions.60 The government replaced the carbon tax system with a “direct action plan,” which included an A$2.55 billion Emissions Reduction Fund (ERF) that would pay emitters for reducing emissions rather than charging them to emit.61 The ERF, which focused on specific emissions-reduction projects rather than emissions overall, was the Liberal Party’s main instrument to reduce emissions by 5% below 2000 levels by 2020.62

Rescinding the MRRT was another campaign promise, which Abbott claimed would contribute over A$13 billion of savings to the federal budget by eliminating spending associated with the tax, including superannuation contributions for low-income individuals and stipends for households with school-aged children. Disagreeing with Abbott’s attempt to dismantle the tax, the Labor’s Treasury spokesman commented, “We have a fundamental view in the Labor Party that the minerals of Australia belong to all Australians and there’s an obligation on Government to ensure that wealth is spread right through Australia from the mining boom.”63 Nevertheless, the MRRT was successfully repealed a few months after the carbon tax, in September 2014.

In 2015 Abbott claimed that he had taken the budget situation “from out of control to manageable,” and presented a budget that was a marked change from the previous one, as government spending increased and certain welfare programs were expanded.64 Notably, the budget included A$5.5 billion for small businesses and A$3.5 billion for child care; Joe Hockey, the Treasurer in Abbott’s government, urged Australians to “get out there and have a go.”65 However, the budget deficit was estimated to have grown to A$44.6 billion by 2015.

Still, Australia’s economy continued to grow, albeit slower (2.2%) in 2015. In an attempt to stimulate growth and promote investment in the non-mining sector, the RBA lowered interest rates to 2%. But manufacturing continued to suffer. When General Motors had earlier announced its withdrawal from Australia, its CEO commented that “the decision to end manufacturing in Australia reflects the perfect storm of negative influences . . . this includes the sustained strength of the Australian dollar, high cost of production, small domestic market and arguably the most competitive and fragmented auto market in the world.”66 Ford then made a similar announcement, followed by Toyota. By 2017, the end of car manufacturing in Australia led to an estimated loss of 200,000 direct and indirect jobs, adding to the countries unemployment rate of over 6%. 67


The Shadow of China

After more than two decades of double-digit growth, China had become the second largest economy in the world and the dominant economic and political force in Asia. All of this economic growth, for a population of 1.4 billion people, meant that China needed resources. The Chinese government’s commitment to industrialization sent multiple Chinese companies to Australia in search of raw materials ranging from steel to oil to coal. Rio Tinto’s CEO, Tom Albanese, stated, “Commodity


10

Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China 720-028


demand in China is… a vast structural shift reflecting urbanization and industrialization of hundreds of millions of people.”68 By 2009, China had surpassed Japan as Australia’s largest export market, reaching 40% of Australia’s exports (up from 5% in 2001) by 2019 (see Exhibit 11b).

The picture on the commodities front, however, was not all positive. Officials faced growing challenges with Chinese investments in Australia, which many citizens viewed with caution, even hostility. Established in 1975, the Foreign Investment Review Board (FIRB) was responsible for examining and recommending proposals made by foreign entities seeking to begin direct investment in Australia. While serving only as an advisory panel, the FIRB recommended suitable proposals for further approval by the Commonwealth government.

The FIRB’s deferral of some investments cast question marks on other Chinese investments waiting for approval, including Chinalco’s proposed US$19.5 billion investment in Rio Tinto. In June 2009, Rio Tinto decided to walk away from the deal with Chinalco, which would have been the single biggest foreign direct investment (FDI) made by China at the time, instead opting for a joint venture with their domestic rival BHP Billiton. Rio Tinto’s decision to forgo the deal with Chinalco stemmed from a concern that the FIRB would squash the proposal. Other resource acquisitions by Chinese firms were made in coal, oil and steel.

Over the course of the next decade, China’s involvement in Australia’s economy continued to grow – not just in resources, but also in infrastructure, real estate and education. These investments had to be approved by the FIRB, which stated that its decisions were made based on whether such investments came into conflict with Australia’s “national interest.” One senator ran a television ad attacking Chinese investments: “The Australian government would never be allowed to buy a mine in China. So why would we allow the Chinese government to buy and control a key strategic asset in our country?”69 Australian citizens also exhibited some discontent. A 2016 poll indicated that 59% of Australians believed that the government was allowing too much foreign investment from China.70

As mining assets came under increased scrutiny, Chinese interests began purchasing more infrastructure – both ports and utilities. In 2013, the State Grid Corporation of China bought a majority stake in Jemena, an electricity distributor in Victoria. In 2015, the Port of Darwin was leased for 99 years to the Landbridge Group, a Chinese company with extensive connections to the Chinese Communist Party.71 This was in spite of U.S. President Obama’s “Pivot to Asia” in 2011, stationing 2,500 U.S. marines at a base in the Darwin port. Other Chinese companies acquired significant stakes in the Ports of Melbourne and Newcastle. In 2016, the government blocked the Chinese purchase of Ausgrid – the country’s largest electricity distributor.72

As China’s wealth increased, its citizens interests in Australia turned increasingly towards real estate. Between 2009 and 2019, thousands of investments were made in commercial and residential properties. In 2016, then-Treasurer Scott Morrison actually blocked the planned sale of S. Kidman and Co. to two Chinese companies. The Kidman ranch, the largest in Australia, was the size of Ireland.73 As a result of these concerns, the Australian government strengthened is foreign investment review process, promulgating new rules that, among other things, closed the loophole that allowed the Port of Darwin lease. In 2017, a Critical Infrastructure Center was established to advise the FIRB. The following year, the Australian government enacted the Security and Critical Infrastructure Act of 2018, increasing oversight on the ownership of infrastructural assets. [See Exhibit 15 for the FIRB’s approvals of recent investments into Australia.]

At the same time, Australia had every reason to tread cautiously, given that China was Australia’s biggest export market and reportedly the single biggest buyer of Australian government debt. The larger picture seemed to indicate that Australia was part of a broader Chinese strategy to secure natural


11

720-028 Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China



resources around the world as Chinese companies—mostly state-owned enterprises— invested billions of dollars in other resource-rich countries such as Sudan and Congo. China, moreover, lagged far behind Australia’s other foreign investors in terms of actual investment amounts (Exhibit 16). The potential ownership of Australian mineral and infrastructural assets by Chinese state-owned companies had created significant public concern.

China’s educational and cultural influence in Australia also came under fire. Australia was home to 1.2 million people of Chinese descent; about 40% of whom were born in China. Australia was host to dozens of Chinese-language media outlets, many of which were allegedly under Beijing’s influence.74 For instance, Confucius Institutes had been established at 13 universities in Australia. Their purpose was to influence perceptions of China. “Li Changchun, a Politburo member, had said the Institutes were ‘an important part of China’s overseas propaganda set-up.’ Deputy Education Minister Hao Ping has noted that ‘establishing Confucius Institutes is a strategic plan for increasing our soft power.’”75 In August 2019, the government announced the creation of a new University Foreign Interference Task Force, designed to address growing concerns regarding freedom of speech, technology transfer, cyber intrusion and other matters.76

Security was at the heart of Australia’s friction with China. In 2017, the Australian government passed the Telecommunications Sector Security Reforms, imposing the duty to protect their own networks from unauthorized access or interference. This law became known as the “anti-Huawei bill.” Just a year later, the Australian government banned Huawei and ZTE from supplying equipment for Australia’s 5G network. Yet China’s growing influence over the Indo-Pacific region - what Canberra called “our region” in a 2016 defense paper - was perhaps the truest test of political v. economic loyalties.77 The Australian government was increasingly concerned about China’s assertion of ownership and control of the South China Sea. In response, it had undertaken a military modernization program, planning to commit A$200 billion by the mid-2020s. The Australian navy would purchase 12 attack submarines, three anti-air destroyers, nine anti-submarine frigates, and two dozen patrol boats. The Royal Air Force would expand its fleet of F-35A joint strike fighters. Spending on cybersecurity would also ramp up.78

In a 2018 article in the Australian Journal of International Affairs, Rory Medcalf dismissed as “myth” that Australia faces some crude choice, “some fundamental decision about whether to go all the way in strategic terms with top trade partner China or long-standing ally America.”79 Medcalf noted that China would like to weaken Australia’s alliance with the United States and its position as the dominant power in the Indo-Pacific. He added that China is “not going to liberalize – indeed, under Xi Jinping it was going the other way.” Chinese “assertiveness, coercion and military modernization were threatening the regional balance and rules-based order….” He called for a “reality check”, quoting from Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull’s (2015-2018) speech introducing the 2017 law on foreign influence, which Turnbull said was built on four pillars – sunlight, enforcement, deterrence and capability.80 Or as it was put more recently in an article about Morrison’s biggest foreign policy test, “Australia now finds itself caught between two different forms of revisionism: the strategic revisionism of Xi Jinping’s China and the economic revisionism of Donald Trump’s United States.”81

Two More Liberal Prime Ministers

Amidst an increasing deficit, party infighting and decreasing popularity, Abbott was challenged by Malcolm Turnbull, who gave up his post as Communications Minister to do so. Turnbull, who had earlier led the Liberal Party, was less conservative than Abbott – more willing to recognize same-sex marriage and Rudd’s carbon trading scheme. He claimed that Abbott was not providing the “economic leadership” that Australia needed. By a 54-44 snap party leadership vote on September 14, 2015 he


12

Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China 720-028


became the leader of the ruling party. He was instated as prime minister the next day. In the federal election the following year, Turnbull led the Liberal Party to a single-seat victory.

Because of the Liberal Party’s narrow margin in Parliament, the Turnbull government experienced difficulty getting things done. In 2017, his government faced an energy crisis. Same-sex marriage was legalized, but only after a brutal public debate. An eligibility crisis arose over several members of parliament with dual citizenship. Policy for asylum seekers remained a political wedge between the moderate and conservative wings of the Liberal Party. The Obama administration agreed to accept refugees from Nauru and Manus in return for Australia’s acceptance of Central American refugees. But then, in a congratulatory phone conversation with President-elect Donald Trump, Turnbull was accused of “broker[ing] many a stupid deal in business;” taking 1,250 refugees from Nauru and Manus to the United States, “will make me look terrible,” said Trump.82 The phone call ended abruptly.

By 2018, the ideological split in the Liberal Party had evolved into an insurgency that finished Turnbull in August. In his resignation, he especially addressed the issue of climate change:

[T]he Coalition finds it very hard to get agreement on anything to do with emissions. I mean, the National Energy Guarantee was, or is, a vitally important piece of economic reform. It remains the government’s policy, of course. But with a one-seat majority in the House, unless you can command all or almost all your votes you can’t get it passed….The emissions issues and climate policy issues have the same problem within the Coalition, of, you know, bitterly entrenched views that are actually sort of more ideological views than views based, as I say, in engineering and economics.83

As it turned out, this issue would become Scott Morrison’s biggest problem. Just over a year after becoming Prime Minister, in September 2019, Morrison addressed the United Nations on climate change.

Australia is also taking real action on climate change and we’re getting results. We are successfully balancing our global responsibilities with sensible and practical policies to secure our environmental and economic future. Australia’s internal and global critics on climate change willingly overlook or perhaps ignore our achievements as the facts simply don’t fit the narrative they wish to project about our contribution. Australia is responsible for just 1.3 percent of global emissions. Australia is doing our bit on climate change, and we reject any suggestion to the contrary. By 2020, Australia will have overachieved on our Kyoto

commitments, reducing our greenhouse gas emissions by 367 million tons more than required to meet our 2020 Kyoto targets…..Australia will also meet our Paris commitments, as well.84

Response to this speech was deeply negative. The Climate Council’s chief executive remarked that it was “colossal bulls**t.” Anthony Albanese, the Labor leader, said the government should stop pretending “black is white.” Apparently, the government was using credits from the Kyoto Agreement as an “accounting trick” to achieve its Paris targets.85

Climate Change and Brush Fires

Although cooler conditions and rain had brought some respite by February 1st 2020, more than 60 fires were still burning in the states of New South Wales and Victoria, Australia. Thirty people had been killed, 110,000 square kilometers burned, thousands of homes destroyed and nearly a billion creatures consumed by flame. Scott Morrison, the Prime Minister of Australia, had not distinguished himself in this emergency. First, he’d given a speech in September on climate change, where he



13

720-028 Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China



purported that Australia was doing a fine job reducing its carbon emissions.86 Then, he chose to go to Hawaii on vacation as the brushfires raged before Christmas. His popularity rating plunged; satisfaction with Morrison fell from 50% September 29th to 39% by January 12th.87

By late September, Queensland had reported more than 80 ongoing fires, with 50 in New South Wales. With summer still two months away, state fire authorities were increasingly concerned. The normal brushfires were being fueled, in part, by drought conditions that had prevailed for two years in eastern Australia. Prime Minister Morrison defended the government’s three-pillar drought strategy, comprised of relief for farmers, support for rural communities and funding for long-term drought resilience. The total package was worth A$7 billion.88 By November, the drought, heat and wind-fueled brushfires had reached emergency proportions. Although Queensland declared a state of emergency on November 9, two dozen homes and 170,000 hectares were burned during the two succeeding weeks. It was far worse in New South Wales, where six people had died, 600 homes were lost and 1.6 million hectares burned.

Both states were criticized for insufficient preparation. A group of fire chiefs from several states complained that larger and more frequent “brushfires are a symptom of climate change,” but the government “fundamentally doesn’t like talking about climate change.”89 By Christmas, eastern Australia was deep in a fire crisis. While the Prime Minister and his family had left for a vacation in Hawaii, fire destroyed thousands of homes, thousands of head of cattle, 46 million acres of bush, and killed 34 people. An estimated one billion animals had been slaughtered, with some endangered species driven towards extinction. Tourism revenues tanked, smoke billowed across the Pacific to Chile and Argentina, and NASA estimated that 337 million tons of CO2 were emitted.90 When Morrison did return, he visited the fire-ravaged town of Cobargo, in New South Wales. “You are out,” said one man referring to Morrison’s Liberal Party: “Go on, piss off.” Others refused to shake his hand.91


Covid-19 and Recovery

Australia experienced its second wave in June-August of 2020, with cases rising to 550 cases per day, but deaths only at 59. A third smaller wave, from the Delta variant, began in July of 2021, reaching 224 cases daily by August. The country had imposed sharp lock-downs for each wave, city by city. Sydney’s lockdown was extended four weeks, and Melbourne had entered a hard lockdown (no one going out except to get groceries). And because of limited access to vaccines, only 16% of the population was fully vaccinated by August.

Scott Morrison had more or less redeemed himself through deft handling of the COVID-19 pandemic. But these new outbreaks were exceedingly frustrating to the populace. Moreover, his popularity with women had also suffered due to allegations of sexual misconduct in his administration. Still, pundits forecast that the Liberal Party would remain in power through the 2022 election.


Australia’s Four Cs

Australia’s four Cs – commodities, competitiveness, climate and China – defined the macro-political challenges facing Scott Morrison’s administration. Australia was rich in commodities, which now dominated its exports. Commodities however, by nature, were characterized by sharp swings in demand, and price. While heavy, often foreign, investments had built the country’s capacity to produce minerals, fuels and food, reliance on these sources of wealth had concentrated Australia’s dependence on markets in China. By raising wages without increasing productivity, their development had further



14

Australia: Commodities, Competitiveness, Climate and China 720-028


weakened the rich country’s competitiveness in manufactured goods. While services had become the core of Australia’s competitiveness, more research and entrepreneurship was needed to keep the country near the front of development.

Yet two of the Cs – climate and China – seemed to represent existential issues over which Australia could only have partial control. Morrison was right. Australia was only responsible for 1.3% of global carbon emissions. Even with maximum effort to mitigate its contributions to climate change, other large countries (especially China and the US) would have to deal with the coming crisis. That left China as the crux of Australia’s future in South East Asia. China was huge, authoritarian and aggressive. Morrison’s Australia would need to charter a delicate course between economic cooperation and security independence.

Morrison knew this… the question was, “how?”
